d=text-link&amp;merchantName=1Password&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiIyOWQwNzM2Ny03ZmZhLTRlMDUtOWE3Zi1jMWRkMTk0MzA2MzAiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly8xcGFzc3dvcmQuY29tLyIsImNvbnRlbnRVdWlkIjoiYTY0OWQ5ZDYtMTBjMy0zNWFmLTk0YzItZGZlOTE5MjUxNTZhIn0&amp;signature=AQAAAedaFskljJO_nkmkybdzZwHxi54DX1OYVqiYqmgVWc-l&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2F1password.com%2F">1Password</a>来保存他们的私人信息，经过测试后，原因就很清楚了。该服务包括行业标准加密、除了主密码之外只有您知道的“秘密密钥”、零知识策略（意味着不保留任何数据）以及其他安全功能，例如频繁审核和错误赏金计划。</p><p>另外，1Password 应用程序具有非常直观的感觉。下载教程可帮助您将其他管理器的密码导入到 1Password，这样您就不会觉得自己是从头开始。它还清楚地评估每个密码的强度，并在保险库中提供“打开和填充”选项，以便您可以更快地进入所需的网站。我们还喜欢扫描设置代码的选项，可以轻松地将您的帐户连接到移动设备，而无需进行太多繁琐的输入。</p><p>个人订阅价格为每月 3 美元，附带无限的密码、项目和 1 GB 的保管库文档存储空间。它还允许您共享密码、信用卡信息和其他保存的凭据。如果您每月支付 5 美元升级到家庭计划，则最多可以邀请 5 个人（再加上每人每月 1 美元）成为保险库的一部分。</p><ul><li><p><strong>层数：</strong> 4</p></li><li><p><strong>定价：</strong>个人 3 美元/月，家庭 5 美元/月，团队入门包 20 美元/月，企业每位用户 8 美元/月</p></li><li><p><strong>兼容性：</strong> macOS、iOS、Windows、Android、Linux、Chrome、Firefox、Safari、Brave、Edge、命令行</p></li></ul><h2>最佳免费密码管理器：Bitwarden</h2><p><core-commerce id="ff15057c13134c979a0870b47876b8d3" data-type="product-list"></p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:14;pos:1" href="https://bitwarden.com/">Bitwarden 的</a>免费计划包括在无限数量的设备上提供无限的密码，这比我们从一些竞争对手那里看到的要多。存在一些缺点，例如您只能与其他用户共享保管库项目，但我们认为这是一个公平的权衡。</p><p> Bitwarden 基于开源代码，这意味着 GitHub 上的任何人都可以审核它，这是一个很好的安全措施。在个人层面上，它包括对您的信息进行安全审核，例如数据泄露报告，可以让您了解密码何时泄露以及何时需要更改密码。此外，它在我们测试的平台上广泛可用，包括 Windows 和 iOS，具有一定程度的自定义、访问保管库的选项等。</p><p> Bitwarden 可能是最好的免费密码管理器，但它确实有付费版本，我们确实认为这是值得的。个人每年 10 美元，家庭每年 40 美元，即可解锁加密文件存储、紧急访问、无限制共享等。但免费版本附带了基础知识，可以让任何人轻松设置密码管理。</p><ul><li><p><strong>层数：</strong> 3</p></li><li><p><strong>定价：</strong>免费，Teams 组织每用户 3 美元/月，Enterprise 组织每用户 5 美元/月</p></li><li><p><strong>兼容性：</strong> macOS、iOS、Windows、Android、Linux、Chrome、Firefox、Safari、Brave、Edge、Vivaldi、Opera、Tor、DuckDuckGo（Mac 版）、命令行</p></li></ul><h2>跨平台可用性的最佳密码管理器：NordPass</h2><p><core-commerce id="a86204c6b5004ba0a5c0cd3571100c6e" data-type="product-list"></p><p> Across password managers we tested, cross-platform availability was relatively similar. Most are widely available across web browsers and different operating systems, including our other top picks on this list. But we wanted to give a nod to <a data-i13n="cpos:15;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsImxhbmRpbmdVcmwiOiJodHRwczovL25vcmRwYXNzLmNvbS8iLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6ImE2NDlkOWQ2LTEwYzMtMzVhZi05NGMyLWRmZTkxOTI1MTU2YSJ9&amp;signature=AQAAAXc3dvFt_FBTUl4eh8nwWwcOj_8uRtp4H_WvfMoCusWk&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fnordpass.com%2F">NordPass</a> here because of how easy the service makes it to access your vault from any platform.</p><p> NordPass has a free option with unlimited passwords and syncs across devices. A $2-per-month premium subscription keeps you logged in when switching devices, comes with security notifications and allows for item sharing. A family subscription comes with six premium accounts and only costs $4 per month. This makes it a pretty good budget option as well. Besides the pairing code to connect accounts, NordPass is a pretty standard password manager. Scanning a code gets me from my laptop to mobile device to work computer super easily. If you&#39;re constantly switching devices and those extra few seconds save your sanity, it&#39;s worth considering.</p><ul><li><p> <strong>Number of tiers:</strong> 3</p></li><li><p> <strong>Pricing:</strong> Free, $2/per month for Premium, $4/month for Family</p></li><li><p> <strong>Compatibility:</strong> macOS, iOS, Windows, Android, Linux, Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Opera, Edge</p></li></ul><h2> Best password manager for shared access: Dashlane</h2><p><core-commerce id="e512d97e6be44fba96f1362969567b59" data-type="product-list"></p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:16;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Dashlane;elmt:;" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=05a8faef-22e0-48ab-a365-0cc59778dc54&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Dashlane&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiIwNWE4ZmFlZi0yMmUwLTQ4YWItYTM2NS0wY2M1OTc3OGRjNTQiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGFzaGxhbmUuY29tLyIsImNvbnRlbnRVdWlkIjoiYTY0OWQ5ZDYtMTBjMy0zNWFmLTk0YzItZGZlOTE5MjUxNTZhIn0&amp;signature=AQAAATgyIRk0s8jpy1K1ohYYrEeJBH8EG2HW8Y3B-l7cs7a-&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dashlane.com%2F">Dashlane</a> has four subscription options: A free user gets access to one device with unlimited passwords; an advanced user pays $3 per month to get upgraded to unlimited devices and dark web monitoring; for $5 per month, a premium user also gets VPN access and an $7.49-per-month family plan includes access for up to 10 people.</p><p> It met all the criteria we looked for, but with a clear emphasis on sharing credentials. Dashlane highlights “secure sharing” starting at its free level, which is a feature that some competitors keep behind a paywall. Access for up to 10 members in a family plan is one of the bigger plans we&#39;ve seen as well. While we were testing it, password sharing seemed front of mind with a tab dedicated to it in Dashlane&#39;s browser extension. Arguably the biggest caveat here, though, is lack of Linux support.</p><ul><li><p> <strong>Number of tiers:</strong> 4</p></li><li><p> <strong>Pricing:</strong> Free, $3/month for Advanced, $5/month for Premium, $7/month for Friends and Family</p></li><li><p> <strong>Compatibility:</strong> macOS, iOS, Android, Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Brave, Edge, Opera</p></li></ul><h2> FAQs</h2><h3> Why use a password manager?</h3><p> Using a password manager can enhance your online security. They store all of your complex passwords and autofill them as needed, so that you can have unique, strong passwords across the web without remembering each of them yourself. In many cases, passwords are your first defense against attack, and a reliable manager makes it easier to keep track of them all.</p><h3> How secure are password managers?</h3><p> Password managers are a secure way to store your credentials. Experts in the field generally agree that the benefits of accessibility when storing complex passwords outweigh the possibility of attack, like what happened with LastPass. But with any service, it can vary from provider to provider. You should look out for zero-knowledge policies, regular security audits, pentests, bug bounty programs and encryption when choosing the right password manager for you.</p><h3> What if I forget my master password?</h3><p> Forgetting a master password won&#39;t necessarily lock you out for good, but the recovery process varies from provider to provider. Some services give you a “security key” at sign up to enter when you log into new devices. It can also be used to securely recover your account because it&#39;s a random string of keys stored locally that only you have access to. Other services, however, have no way to recover your vault. So creating a master password that you won&#39;t forget is important.</p><h3> How can I make a good master password?</h3><p> A good master password should be unique, with the longest number of characters allowed and uppercase letters, lowercase letters, numbers and special characters. Experts often recommended thinking of it like a “passphrase” instead of a “password” to make it easier to remember. For example, you can take a sentence like “My name is Bob Smith” and change it to “Myn@m3isB0b5m!th” to turn it into a secure master password that you won&#39;t forget.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/best-password-manager-134639599.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/best-password-manager-134639599.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> a649d9d6-10c3-35af-94c2-dfe91925156a</guid><dc:crea